\begin_layout Section
Contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This research introduces a novel and integrated framework for coordinating fully heterogeneous robotic fleets,
 including aerial,
 aquatic,
 legged,
 wheeled,
 and surface agents within high-risk,
 real-world disaster environments.
 The key expected contributions are outlined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
1.
 Unified Traversability Risk Assessment Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A centralised framework is developed that quantitatively assesses terrain risk using a probabilistic model.
 It fuses both sensor-based and map-based metrics to evaluate environmental suitability for each locomotion type.
 This approach accounts for physical and operational constraints,
 enabling consistent comparisons of terrain traversability across all agent types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
2.
 Extension of Lambda Fields to Multi-Robot Decision-Making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work adapts the Lambda field framework,
 traditionally applied to individual robot path planning,
 for use in fleet-level coordination.
 By treating risk as a physically meaningful,
 spatially distributed field,
 it enables heterogeneous agents to make informed decisions based on their locomotion-specific vulnerabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.
 Risk-Aware Task Allocation and Mission Planning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A mission planning algorithm is proposed that dynamically allocates tasks based on agents' capabilities,
 resource states (e.g.,
 energy reserves),
 and environmental risk distributions.
 This ensures that each task is matched to the robot most likely to succeed,
 improving operational robustness and responsiveness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
4.
 Real-Time 3D Map Fusion and Replanning Pipeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hybrid map merging approach is implemented,
 combining global feature matching with local ICP-based refinement.
 This strategy improves localisation and map consistency among agents operating in GPS-denied or spatially disconnected environments.
 The system supports dynamic replanning in response to environmental change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
5.
 Simulation-Based Validation in Disaster Scenarios
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The framework is validated using high-fidelity simulations across urban,
 rural,
 and hybrid disaster landscapes.
 Leveraging platforms like Isaac Sim and OctoMap,
 the evaluation demonstrates the framework’s effectiveness in terrain-aware decision-making,
 risk modelling,
 and coordination under dynamic,
 uncertain conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together,
 these contributions address major challenges in contemporary multi-robot research,
 particularly the lack of frameworks capable of unifying all locomotion types within a risk-aware,
 dynamically adaptive decision-making architecture.
 The work not only introduces technical innovations but also proposes a scalable,
 mission-relevant solution for future real-world deployments in disaster response and exploration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The literature reviewed throughout this chapter establishes a clear need for a unified,
 risk-aware coordination strategy for heterogeneous multi-robot systems.
 Existing approaches have made significant strides in dual or tri-locomotion coordination,
 path planning,
 mapping,
 and fleet control;
 however,
 they often operate within narrow domains and rely on simplifying assumptions unsuited to real-world,
 high-stakes environments like SAR.
 This research seeks to build on and extend these foundations by introducing a cohesive framework that can support true heterogeneity,
 dynamic replanning,
 and risk-based task distribution in realistic terrain.
 The following chapter presents the formal problem formulation underpinning this framework,
 laying out the assumptions,
 mathematical models,
 and performance objectives that guide the development of the system.
\end_layout

